Definition: from {{h1438}}; feller (i.e. warrior); Gidon, an Israelite; Gideon.
a primitive root; to fell a tree; generally, to destroy anything; cut (asunder, in sunder, down, off), hew down.
from {{h1431}}; I have made great; Giddalti, an Israelite; Giddalti.
or (prolonged) גְּדַלְיָהוּ; from {{h1431}} and {{h3050}}; Jah has become great; Gedaljah, the name of five Israelites; Gedaliah.
from {{h1431}}; stout; Giddel, the name of one of the Nethinim, also of one of 'Solomon's servants'; Giddel.
from {{h1431}} (in the sense of twisting); thread, i.e. a tassel or festoon; fringe, wreath.
from {{h1431}}; magnitude (literally or figuratively); greatness, stout(-ness).
from {{h1431}}; large (literally or figuratively); great, grew.

a primitive root; properly, to twist (compare {{h1434}}), i.e.; to be (causatively make) large (in various senses, as in body, mind, estate or honor, also in pride); advance, boast, bring up, exceed, excellent, be(-come, do, give, make, wax), great(-er, come to... estate,   things), grow(up), increase, lift up, magnify(-ifical), be much set by, nourish (up), pass, promote, proudly (spoken), tower.
from an unused root (meaning to heap up); a stack of sheaves; by analogy, a tomb; shock (stack) (of corn), tomb.
or גַּדיָה; the same as {{h1415}}; a river brink; bank.
feminine of {{h1423}}; a young female goat; kid.
or גְּדֻלָּה; (shortened) or (less accurately) גְּדוּלָּה; feminine of {{h1419}}; greatness; (concretely) mighty acts; dignity, great things(-ness), majesty.
or (shortened) גִּדֻּף; and (feminine) גִּדּוּפָהxlit giddûphâh corrected to giddûwphâh; or גִּדֻּפָה; from {{h1422}}; vilification; reproach, reviling.
feminine passive participle of {{h1442}}; a revilement; taunt.
from the same as {{h1415}}; a young goat (from browsing); kid.
from {{h1409}}; fortunate; Gadi, an Israelite; Gadi.
patronymically from {{h1410}}; a Gadite (collectively) or descendants of Gad; Gadites, children of Gad.
intensive for {{h1424}}; Gaddi, an Israelite; Gaddi.
from {{h1409}} and {{h410}}; fortune of God; Gaddiel, an Israelite; Gaddiel.
feminine of {{h1498}} and meaning the same; that (he had robbed) (which he took violently away), spoil, violence.
(Aramaic) corresponding to {{h1460}}; the middle; midst, same, there-(where-) in.
another form for {{h1460}}; the back; back.
a primitive root; to remove (a bandage from a wound, i.e. heal it); cure.
probably a clerical error for {{h2088}}; this; this.
a primitive root; to prostrate oneself; cast self down, stretch self.
from {{h1455}}; a cure; medicine.
patrial from {{h1445}}; a Gederite, or inhabitant of Geder; Gederite.
plural of {{h1448}}; walls; Gederoth, a place in Palestine; Gederoth.
dual of {{h1448}}; double wall; Gederothajim, a place in Palestine; Gederothaim.
patrial from {{h1449}}; a Gederathite, or inhabitant of Gederah; Gederathite.
feminine of {{h1447}}; inclosure (especially for flocks); (sheep-) cote (fold) hedge, wall.
the same as {{h1448}}; (with the article) Gederah, a place in Palestine; Gederah, hedges.
or (fully) גְּדוֹר; from {{h1443}}; inclosure; Gedor, a place in Palestine; also the name of three Israelites; Gedor.
from {{h1443}}; a circumvallation; by implication, an inclosure; fence, hedge, wall.
from {{h1443}}; a circumvallation; wall.
; the same as {{h1444}}; Geder, a place in Palestine; Geder.
a primitive root; to hack (with words), i.e. revile; blaspheme, reproach.
a primitive root; to wall in or around; close up, fence up, hedge, inclose, make up (a wall), mason, repairer.
from {{h1438}}; a cutting (i.e. desolation); Gidom, a place in Palestine; Gidom.
from {{h1438}}; warlike (compare {{h1439}}); Gidoni, an Israelite; Gideoni.
a primitive root; properly, to hollow or arch, i.e. (figuratively) close; to shut; shut.
a primitive root; to breathe out, i.e. (by implication) expire; die, be dead, give up the ghost, perish.
or (shortened) גֹּלָה; active participle feminine of {{h1540}}; exile; concretely and collectively exiles; (carried away), captive(-ity), removing.
prolonged for {{h1465}}; a body, whether alive or dead; (dead) body, carcase, corpse.

rarely (shortened) גֹּי; apparently from the same root as {{h1465}} (in the sense of massing); a foreign nation; hence, a Gentile; also (figuratively) a troop of animals, or a flight of locusts; Gentile, heathen, nation, people.
probably from {{h1468}}; a quarry (as a place of cutting stones); Gozan, a province of Assyria; Gozan.
patronymically from {{h1476}}; a Gunite (collectively with article prefix) or descendants of Guni; Gunites.
probably from {{h1598}}; protected; Guni, the name of two Israelites; Guni.
of uncertain derivation; a pit; pit.
from {{h1473}}; captive; Golan, a place east of the Jordan; Golan.
a primitive root (akin to {{h1413}}); to crowd upon, i.e. attack; invade, overcome.
feminine of {{h1460}}; the back, i.e. (by extension) the person; body.
the same as {{h1465}}; exaltation; (figuratively) arrogance; lifting up, pride.
(Aramaic) corresponding to {{h1466}}; pride.
from {{h1342}} (corresponding to {{h1354}}); the back; by analogy, the middle; among, back, body.
a primitive root; to dig; husbandman.
from {{h1461}}; the locust (from its grubbing as a larvae); grasshopper, × great.
of uncertain derivation; Gog, the name of an Israelite, also of some northern nation; Gog.
a primitive root (compare {{h1494}}); properly, to shear off; but used only in the (figuratively) sense of passing rapidly; bring, cut off.
or (shortened) גֹזָלlemma גזָל missing vowel, corrected to גֹזָל; from {{h1497}}; a nestling (as being comparatively nude of feathers); young (pigeon).
(Aramaic) corresponding to {{h1489}}; a treasurer; treasurer.
from {{h1464}}; Gad, a son of Jacob, including his tribe and its territory; also a prophet; Gad.
a primitive root (compare {{h1464}}); to crowd; also to gash (as if by pressing into); assemble (selves by troops), gather (selves together, self in troops), cut selves.
by reduplication from {{h1413}} (in the sense of cutting) cleft; Gudgodah, a place in the Desert; Gudgodah.
from an unused root (meaning to cut off); a border of a river (as cut into by the stream); bank.
(Aramaic) corresponding to {{h1413}}; to cut down; hew down.
or גְּדֻדָה; (feminine) from {{h1413}}; a furrow (as cut); furrow.
from {{h1413}}; a crowd (especially of soldiers); army, band (of men), company, troop (of robbers).

or גָּדֹל; (shortened) from {{h1431}}; great (in any sense); hence, older; also insolent; aloud, elder(-est),   exceeding(-ly),   far, (man of) great (man, matter, thing,-er,-ness), high, long, loud, mighty, more, much, noble, proud thing, × sore, (×) very.
feminine participle passive of {{h1413}}; an incision; cutting.
from {{h1497}}; plunder, i.e. violence; violence, violent perverting.. gozal. See {{h1469}}.
from {{h1497}}; robbery, or (concretely) plunder; robbery, thing taken away by violence.
a primitive root (akin to {{h1468}}); to cut off, i.e. portion out; take.
(Aramaic) corresponding to {{h1489}}; treasurer.
patrial from the unused name of a place apparently in Palestine; a Gizonite or inhabitant of Gizoh; Gizonite.
feminine from {{h1494}}; a fleece; fleece.
from {{h1494}}; shearer; Gazez, the name of two Israelites; Gazez.
a primitive root (akin to {{h1468}}); to cut off; specifically to shear a flock or shave the hair; figuratively to destroy an enemy; cut off (down), poll, shave, (sheep-) shear(-er).
a primitive root; to pluck off; specifically to flay, strip or rob; catch, consume, exercise (robbery), pluck (off), rob, spoil, take away (by force, violence), tear.
from {{h1491}}; something cut, i.e. dressed stone; hewed, hewn stone, wrought.
intensive of {{h1399}}; Gibbar, an Israelite; Gibbar.
from {{h1397}} and {{h410}}; man of God; Gabriel, an archangel; Garbriel.
(Aramaic) intensive of {{h1400}}; valiant, or warrior; mighty.
probably by reduplication from {{h1342}}; a roof; by analogy, the top of an altar; roof (of the house), (house) top (of the house).
from {{h1413}} (in the sense of cutting); coriander seed (from its furrows); coriander.
feminine of {{h1376}}; mistress; lady, mistress.
intensive from {{h1389}}; a hilly spot; Gibbethon, a place in Palestine; Gibbethon.
a variation of {{h1409}}; Fortune, a Babylonian deity; that troop.
from {{h1464}} (in the sense of distributing); fortune; troop.
from {{h1494}}; a fleece (as shorn); also mown grass; fleece, mowing, mown grass.
of foreign derivation; treasurer; treasurer.
or (shortened) גֻּר; perhaps from {{h1481}}; a cub (as still abiding in the lair), especially of the lion; whelp, young one.
the same as {{h1482}}; Gur, a place in Palestine; Gur.
from {{h1479}}; a corpse (as closed to sense); body.

a primitive root; properly, to turn aside from the road (for a lodging or any other purpose), i.e. sojourn (as a guest); also to shrink, fear (as in a strange place); also to gather for hostility (as afraid); abide, assemble, be afraid, dwell, fear, gather (together), inhabitant, remain, sojourn, stand in awe, (be) stranger, × surely.

or (shortened) גֹּרָל; from an unused root meaning to be rough (as stone); properly, a pebble, i.e. a lot (small stones being used for that purpose); figuratively, a portion or destiny (as if determined by lot); lot.
or rather (by permutation) גִּישׁ; of uncertain derivation; a mass of earth; clod.
or (feminine) גֹּרָה; a variation of {{h1482}}; whelp.
from {{h1481}} and {{h1168}}; dwelling of Baal; Gur-Baal, a place in Arabia; Gur-baal.
